            <h2>1. The Reveal Shot</h2>
            <p>
                The reveal shot slowly introduces your subject into the frame, building anticipation for the viewer.
                You can perform this by starting behind a foreground object—such as a tree, cliff, or building—and then 
                flying upward, sideways, or forward to uncover the scene.
            </p>
            <p><strong>How to perform:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Reduce gimbal pitch speed in your settings for smoother motion.</li>
                <li>Start close to a foreground object with your gimbal angled slightly downward.</li>
                <li>Fly backward, forward, or ascend while slowly pitching the gimbal upward to reveal the scene.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>2. The Orbit Shot (Point of Interest)</h2>
            <p>
                The orbit shot circles your subject while keeping it perfectly centered. 
                It’s ideal for showcasing landmarks, landscapes, or even people from all angles in a single smooth motion.
            </p>
            <p><strong>How to perform:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Fly to your desired distance from the subject and keep it framed at the center.</li>
                <li>Move the yaw and roll controls together in opposite directions to create a smooth arc.</li>
                <li>Keep the altitude steady for a balanced cinematic look.</li>
            </ul>

            <figure class="post-image">
                <img src="/images/blog/3-Ways-to-Get-Smooth-Cinematic-Drone-Shots/img2.webp" alt="Lakshapana falls Sri-Lanka" />
