            </figure>

            <h2>3. The Push-In / Pull-Out (Dolly Shot)</h2>
            <p>
                This shot mimics the effect of a camera dolly in film production—either moving toward (push-in) 
                or away from (pull-out) your subject. It’s a simple way to create depth and draw attention to your main focus.
            </p>
            <p><strong>How to perform:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>For a push-in, start far from the subject and fly toward it while keeping the gimbal locked on the subject.</li>
                <li>For a pull-out, start close and fly backward to reveal more of the surroundings.</li>
                <li>Use slow, steady stick inputs to avoid jerky motion.</li>
                <li>Activate a “cinema” or “tripod” flight mode for more precise control.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Final Tips for Smooth Cinematics</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Use slower gimbal and flight control settings to achieve gentle movements.</li>
                <li>Plan your shots before takeoff to save time and battery.</li>
                <li>Fly in calm weather to avoid sudden shakes from wind gusts.</li>
                <li>Experiment with combining moves—like a reveal and an orbit—for unique results.</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                These three fundamental drone shots—the reveal, orbit, and push-in/pull-out—are the foundation of cinematic aerial filmmaking. 
                Master them, and you’ll be able to create footage that feels smooth, engaging, and visually stunning.
            </p>
